      "@type": "Offer",
      "priceSpecification": {
        "@type": "PriceSpecification",
        "price": "89.00",
        "priceCurrency": "USD",
        "description": "Diagnostic fee, waived with repair"
      }
    }
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What's the difference between Wolf DF and GR series — does it matter for repair?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "It's the single most important distinction when diagnosing a Wolf range. DF Series (Dual-Fuel) has a gas rangetop with an electric oven — the oven uses a bake element (bottom) and broil element (top), same as any electric oven. GR Series (all-Gas Range) uses gas in both the rangetop and the oven — the oven has a hot-surface igniter that opens a gas valve. When a DF oven won't heat, we check the bake element and temperature sensor. When a GR oven won't heat, we check the igniter first. Swapping igniters on DF ovens or bake elements on GR ovens fixes nothing — we see shops do this constantly."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "My Wolf burner won't stop clicking after it lights",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Two causes. Most common: moisture in the spark electrode area. The Wolf sparker keeps firing until it senses a flame — if moisture is preventing clean flame sensing, the spark won't stop. Happens after cleaning, boil-overs, or humid coastal air (Malibu and Pacific Palisades see it most often). Solution: dry the electrode and surrounding area thoroughly, 15-minute fix. Second cause: failed spark module stuck in continuous-fire mode. Module replacement $285–$425, 45-minute job. We test with a meter before swapping."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "My Wolf burners ignite but the oven and control panel have no power",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Characteristic DF486G/DF484CG pattern. The burners run on their own dedicated ignition circuit, which is why they light even when the main control is dead. The oven and controls share a circuit that includes a thermal fuse. When the thermal fuse blows (usually from a control board overheating event), everything non-burner goes dead. Fix: replace the thermal fuse ($85) AND identify why it blew — usually a degraded control board that needs replacement too ($520–$780). If we only swap the fuse without fixing the underlying cause, it blows again within weeks. We diagnose both."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How much does Wolf range repair cost?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Diagnostic is $89, waived with repair. Typical Wolf range jobs: spark ignition module $285–$425, surface igniter (per burner) $185–$275, spark electrode $85–$125, bake element (DF Series) $215–$310, broil element (DF Series) $235–$345, oven igniter (GR Series, hot-surface) $245–$340, temperature sensor $155–$225, thermal fuse $85–$145, main control board $520–$780, door gasket $245–$380, red control knob set $180–$240. Labor and parts quoted separately before we start."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can you replace the 'hidden' bake element on the DF486G smaller oven?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes. The small oven on the DF486G has its bake element behind a rear panel rather than exposed in the cavity. Access is through the rear of the small oven — we remove the oven racks and the interior back panel to reach the element mounting, disconnect the two-pin wiring harness, unscrew the brackets, and pull the old element through the panel opening. New element installs the reverse way. Total job about 75 minutes. Element cost $250 OEM, we carry them stocked for the DF486G."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "The lower-tier simmer on my Wolf won't hold low heat",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Wolf dual-stacked burners have separate orifices for the high-output upper tier and the low-output simmer lower tier, each with its own setting on the valve. When the simmer won't hold — pan still boils at the low setting — it's usually a clogged simmer orifice (LP or natural gas, depending on your supply) or a valve that's drifted out of calibration. The simmer orifices are small ($45 part, Natural Gas or LP specific). Cleaning sometimes works; replacement is more reliable. Valve recalibration is a bench-level adjustment we can do on-site for simple drift."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
];
